From now on, code blocks no longer appear inline. Each listing is moved to the Appendix: Source code with a label of the form lst:something, and a placeholder in the body reads “See code \ref{lst:something} in Appendix for the implementation.” — this keeps the body of the book uncluttered while preserving the full computational record.

13.4 Stan: Hamiltonian Monte Carlo with gradients

13.4.1 Overview
Stan is a probabilistic programming language that uses Hamiltonian Monte Carlo with the No-U-Turn Sampler (NUTS) algorithm. By leveraging automatic differentiation to compute gradients of the log-posterior, Stan explores the posterior much more efficiently than Gibbs sampling, especially in high dimensions.
Modern Stan workflows use cmdstanr, a lightweight R interface.


13.4.2 Model structure
A Stan program has five optional blocks, executed in order:

data: Observed quantities, fixed.
transformed data: Derived quantities computed once.
parameters: The target of inference.
transformed parameters: Deterministic functions of parameters.
model: The log-posterior (likelihood + priors).
generated quantities: Posterior predictions.



13.4.3 Example: centered quadratic regression
data {
  int&lt;lower=1&gt; N;
  vector[N] z;
  vector[N] y;
}

parameters {
  real a0;
  real a1;
  real a2;
  real&lt;lower=0&gt; sigma;
}

model {
  // Likelihood
  y ~ normal(a0 + a1 * z + a2 * square(z), sigma);

  // Priors
  a0 ~ normal(0, 20);
  a1 ~ normal(0, 20);
  a2 ~ normal(0, 20);
  sigma ~ normal(0, 10);  // Half-normal (due to lower=0)
}
Key syntax notes:

Type declarations: real, vector[N], int.
Constraints are declared inline: &lt;lower=0&gt;, &lt;upper=1&gt;.
Stan samples unconstrained internally; constraints are handled via smooth transformations (e.g., log for positive parameters).
Standard deviation is natural; no precision.
Vectorized operations (y ~ normal(...) broadcasts over the vector) are encouraged.



13.4.4 Workflow in R with cmdstanr
library(cmdstanr)

# Prepare data
stan_data &lt;- list(
  N = nrow(obsdata),
  z = obsdata$z,
  y = obsdata$y
)

# Compile
mod &lt;- cmdstan_model("quad_centered.stan")

# Sample
fit &lt;- mod$sample(
  data = stan_data,
  chains = 4,
  parallel_chains = 4,
  iter_warmup = 1000,
  iter_sampling = 2000,
  seed = 123
)

# Summary
fit$summary(c("a0", "a1", "a2", "sigma"))

# Diagnostics
fit$cmdstan_diagnose()


13.4.5 Posterior diagnostics in Stan
Stan reports several convergence statistics:

\(\hat{R}\) (potential scale reduction factor): Should be \(&lt; 1.01\). Values \(&gt; 1.05\) indicate poor convergence.
ESS (effective sample size): Bulk ESS and tail ESS. Rule of thumb: both \(\gtrsim 400\) per chain. Low ESS indicates high autocorrelation.
Divergent transitions: Occur when the leapfrog integrator leaves the high-probability region. May indicate a multimodal or heavy-tailed target. Typical remedy: increase adapt_delta (default 0.8) to 0.9 or 0.95.

14.8 Bayesian inference via MCMC
Frequentist GLMs are typically fitted by maximum likelihood using iteratively reweighted least squares (IRLS). The Bayesian approach places a prior on the coefficients and explores the posterior via Markov chain Monte Carlo. Priors are placed on the coefficient scale; weakly informative normal priors such as \(w_k \sim \mathcal{N}(0, s^2)\) are a reasonable default, and standardizing predictors makes a single prior scale meaningful across coefficients.

14.8.1 Logistic regression in Stan
The following Stan model fits logistic regression with weakly informative normal priors:
data {
  int&lt;lower=1&gt; N;
  vector[N] x;
  array[N] int&lt;lower=0, upper=1&gt; y;
}
parameters {
  real w0;
  real w1;
}
model {
  w0 ~ normal(0, 5);
  w1 ~ normal(0, 5);
  y ~ bernoulli_logit(w0 + w1 * x);
}
generated quantities {
  array[N] int y_rep;
  for (i in 1:N) {
    y_rep[i] = bernoulli_logit_rng(w0 + w1 * x[i]);
  }
}
Stan’s bernoulli_logit function is numerically stable; it computes the log-likelihood directly without forming \(\pi_i\) explicitly. The fitted curve below shows a logistic regression with \(w_0 = -0.4\), \(w_1 = 1.2\):


Show code
set.seed(202)
N &lt;- 80
x &lt;- seq(-4, 4, length.out = N)
w0_true &lt;- -0.4
w1_true &lt;- 1.2
eta &lt;- w0_true + w1_true * x
pi &lt;- plogis(eta)  # 1 / (1 + exp(-eta))
y &lt;- rbinom(N, size = 1, prob = pi)

plot(x, y, pch = 19, col = "black", ylim = c(-0.1, 1.1),
     xlab = "x", ylab = "y (0 or 1)", cex = 0.8, las = 1)
lines(x, pi, lwd = 2.5, col = "#b8123e")
grid(col = "gray80")
legend("topleft", legend = c("observed", "true probability"),
       pch = c(19, NA), lty = c(NA, 1), lwd = c(NA, 2.5),
       col = c("black", "#b8123e"), bty = "n")





Simulated binary data (0/1 points) with fitted logistic curve.






14.8.2 Poisson regression in Stan
data {
  int&lt;lower=1&gt; N;
  vector[N] x;
  array[N] int&lt;lower=0&gt; y;
}
parameters {
  real w0;
  real w1;
}
model {
  w0 ~ normal(0, 5);
  w1 ~ normal(0, 5);
  y ~ poisson_log(w0 + w1 * x);
}
generated quantities {
  array[N] int y_rep;
  for (i in 1:N) {
    y_rep[i] = poisson_log_rng(w0 + w1 * x[i]);
  }
}
The poisson_log function computes the Poisson likelihood with log link: given \(\eta = w_0 + w_1 x\), it increments log-probability by \(y \eta - e^\eta - \log(y!)\). The generated quantities block produces posterior predictive replicates for model checking. For an exposure-weighted model, replace the sampling statement with y ~ poisson_log(log(exposure) + w0 + w1 * x). JAGS implements the same models with syntax close to the mathematical form (y[i] ~ dpois(lambda[i]) with log(lambda[i]) &lt;- w0 + w1*x[i], and analogously dbern with logit(pi[i]) for the Bernoulli case); Stan is often more efficient for continuous parameters with strong posterior correlations.
